column168: SHIPMENT CONTAINED 145 GALLON STEEL DRUMS DESIGNED TO HANDLE THIS TYPE OF H JAZARDOUS LIQUID, EACH WA SLINED WITH A PLASTIC LINER TO PROTECT THE DRUM I TSELF FROM THE SECONDARY HAZARD WHICH WAS CORROSIVE, EACH DRUM WEIGHTED 49 LBS. EACH AND EACH DRUM APPEARED TO BE WELL PACKED.  ON WAY TO AIRPORT AFTE R SHIPMENT WAS LOADED TRUCK EITHER HIT A BUMP OR A HOLE AND TWO OF THE DRUM S FELL OVER.  ONE DRUM STAYED CLOSED, THE OTHER DRUM'S WHOLE TOP CAME OFF A ND THE CONTENTS SPILLED IN THE TRUCK.  WHEN THE TRUCK REACHED LUFTHANSAS'S FACILITY THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED.  THE EPA, FIRE DEPT AND FFA WAS NOTIFIED BY LUFTHANSA.  EPA WOULD NOT COME AS THEY SAID IT WAS NOT LARGE ENOUGH SPIL L (20 LITERS) FFA NEVER SHOWED UP, SO THE FIRE DEPT CLEANED UP THE BEST THE Y COULD AND THEN HAZTECH INC. WAS CALLED, WHICH SPECIALIZES IN CLEANING UP AND SECURING DANGEROUS GODS, THEY CLEANED AREA, TRUCK, AND REMAINING DRUMS AND RETURNED THEM TO US.  WE THEN SENT THEM BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECT ION AND THEY REPACED IN EVEN STRONGER PLASTIC (34) DRUMS AND RESENT THEM OF LUFTHANSA TO BRUSSELS BELGIUM.  BELIEVE IT WAS MORE OF A DEFECT IN THE DRU M THAN POOR PACKAGING.  MR. SAMUEL HENDERSON OF HAZTECH INC. STATED THAT ON E OTHER DRUM ALTHOUGH NOT OPEN WAS PACKED IN A PROTECTIVE BARREL BECAUSE IT APPEARED TO BE BULGING AT THE SIDES DUE TO THE HEAT.

WHILE HUMPING TRACK #52 EAST BOUND CLASS, CAR NOTED TO HAVE SPLASH LEAKAGE AT DOME AREA.  CONDUCTOR J.F. WALSH ALLEDGES VAPORS IN AIR CAUSED HEADACHE AND IRRITATED THROAT.  MR. WALSH TAKEN TO HOSPITAL TREATED AND RELEASED.  C AR FOUND TO HAVE 3 MANWAY BOLTS UNSECURED AND 3 OTHERS LOOSE.  GENERAL FORE MAN SECURED MANWAY BOLTS, CAR RELEASED TO SERVICE.

WHEN DRIVER REPORT TO DISPATCHER LIQ LEAKING FORM TRLR.  I CALLED SHIPPER F OR INFORMATION ON THIS MATERIAL.  LARRY SUTTON OF MONSANTO CO TRENTON, MICI GAN GAVE ME INFORMATION AND TOLD ME A RESP. FROM MONSANTO BRIDGEPORT NJ WOU LD BE DISPATCH TO ARA/SMITH'S TERMINAL TO ASSIST.  I CALLED RON GAIEWSKI AR A/STC HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OFFICE IN STAUNTON, VA RON WAS IN COH, OH SO I CAL LED HIM IN COH.  TALKED TO RON, HE TOLD ME TO MOVE THE TRLR. TO THE END OF THE YARD, CALL THE FIRE DEPT. AND CHEMTREC.  CHEMTREC TOLD ME TO GET SODA A SH FOR TRLR, GROUND AND DRIVEWAY FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE DEPT BURLINGTON CO UNTYU HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORD, RESP FROM MONSANTO BRIDGEPORT, NJ. ARRIVED THAN I RECD A CALL FROM GARRY ALLEN OF NJ ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  THJEY SENT A RESP. TO THE SITE.  ALLEN TOLD ME TO CALL IN A CLEAN UP CREW.  THEN HE TALKED TO FIRE CHIEF AND TOLD THEM TO LEAVE.  MR. ALLEN GAVE ME THE NAME S OF THREE COMPANIES FOR CLEAN UP.  MID ATLANTIC DEPTFORD NJ, NEW ENGLAND T RENTON, NJ, O H MATERIAL, TRENTON, NJ.  I CALLED MID ATLANTIC AND WAS TOLD THEY WOULD CALL BACK WHEN THE OWNER RETURNED.  I CALLED NEW ENGLAND TRLR TO ANOTEHFR TRLR.  THEY FOUND 1 DRUM LEAKING, IT HV A 2 BY 4 WHICH USED IN TH E BLOCKING OF DRUM, IN THE DRUM.  THEY REPLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A PLA STIC CONTAINER.  CLEANED ALL THE AREA AROUND THE TRLR. DRIVEWAY AND THE INS IDE OF TRLR.  THEY COMPLETED APPROX 8 PM WITH THE CLEAN UP.  MANSANTO BRIDG EPORT NJ RETURNED TO ARA/SMITH'S TERM. WITH 2 MEN TO RELOAD TRLR AND BLOCKE D DRUMS FOR DELV.
